    "answer": "To solve this problem, we can use the Law of Cosines, which relates the lengths of the sides of a triangle to the cosine of one of its angles.\n\nLet's break down the problem step by step:\n\n1. Sam starts at his campsite and walks eastward for 5 miles, so he is now 5 miles away from his starting point.\n2. Then, he turns 45 degrees northward and walks 8 miles. This creates a right triangle with legs of length 5 miles and 8 miles, and an angle of 45 degrees between them.\n3. We can use the Law of Cosines to find the length of the third side of the triangle, which is the distance from Sam's current position to his starting point.\n\nThe Law of Cosines states that for a triangle with sides of length a, b, and c, and an angle C opposite side c, we have:\n\nc\u00b2 = a\u00b2 + b\u00b2 - 2ab * cos(C)\n\nIn this case, we have a = 5, b = 8, and C = 45 degrees. Plugging these values into the formula, we get:\n\nc\u00b2 = 5\u00b2 + 8\u00b2 - 2(5)(8) * cos(45\u00b0)\nc\u00b2 = 25 + 64 - 80 * cos(45\u00b0)\nc\u00b2 = 89 - 80 * (1/\u221a2)\nc\u00b2 = 89 - 80/\u221a2\nc\u00b2 = (89\u221a2 - 80) / \u221a2\nc\u00b2 = (89 - 40\u221a2) / \u221a2\nc\u00b2 = (89 - 40\u221a2) * (\u221a2 / \u221a2) / \u221a2\nc\u00b2 = (89\u221a2 - 80) / 2\nc\u00b2 = (89 - 40\u221a2) / 2\nc\u00b2 = (89 - 40\u221a2) / 2\nc = \u221a((89 - 40\u221a2) / 2)\n\nNow, we can simplify the expression by rationalizing the denominator:\n\nc = \u221a((89 - 40\u221a2) / 2)\nc = \u221a((89 - 40\u221a2) * (1/2))\nc = \u221a((89 - 40\u221a2) * (\u221a2/\u221a2) / 2)\nc = \u221a((89\u221a2 - 80) / 2\u221a2)\nc = \u221a((89\u221a2 - 80) / 2\u221a2) * (\u221a2 / \u221a2)\nc = \u221a((89\u221a2 - 80) * (\u221a2 / 2) / 2)\nc = \u221a((89\u221a2 - 80) * (\u221a2 / 4))\nc = \u221a((89\u221a2 - 80) * (\u221a2 / 4))\nc = \u221a((89\u221a2 - 80) * (\u221a2 / 4))\nc = \u221a((89\u221a2 - 80) * (\u221a2 / 4))\nc = \u221a((89\u221a2 - 80) * (\u221a2 / 4))\nc = \u221a((89\u221a2 - 80) * (\u221a2 / 4))\nc = \u221a((89\u